---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const ifsDefinition = "A finite set of contraction mappings $\\{f_1, f_2, \\ldots, f_n\\}$ on a complete metric space $(X, d)$.";
const attractorFormula = "$$A = \\bigcup_{i=1}^{n} f_i(A)$$";
const affineFormula = "$$f_i(\\mathbf{x}) = A_i \\mathbf{x} + \\mathbf{b}_i$$";
---
<BaseLayout title="About — IFS Encyclopedia" description="What is an Iterated Function System?">
  <main>
    <h1>About IFS Encyclopedia</h1>

    <h2>What is an Iterated Function System?</h2>
    <p>
      An <strong>Iterated Function System</strong> (IFS) is <span set:html={ifsDefinition}></span>
      Each mapping <em>f<sub>i</sub></em> satisfies a contractivity condition: there exists
      0 &le; <em>c</em> &lt; 1 such that d(f<sub>i</sub>(x), f<sub>i</sub>(y)) &le; c·d(x,y)
      for all x, y in X.
    </p>

    <h2>The Attractor</h2>
    <p>
      By the Banach fixed-point theorem, every IFS has a unique non-empty compact
      <strong>attractor</strong> (also called the invariant set) <em>A</em> satisfying:
    </p>
    <p set:html={attractorFormula}></p>
    <p>
      Starting from any compact set, repeated application of all mappings simultaneously
      converges to this attractor in the Hausdorff metric.
    </p>

    <h2>Affine Form</h2>
    <p>
      IFS mappings can in principle be any contractions — including nonlinear ones such as
      Möbius transformations, polynomial maps, or trigonometric functions. However, the
      most widely studied and computationally tractable case is <strong>affine contractions</strong>
      of the form:
    </p>
    <p set:html={affineFormula}></p>
    <p>
      where <em>A<sub>i</sub></em> is a 2×2 (or n×n) matrix and <strong>b</strong><sub>i</sub>
      is a translation vector. The contractivity condition requires that the spectral radius
      of <em>A<sub>i</sub></em> is less than 1.
      All entries in this encyclopedia use affine (or projective-algebraic) maps.
    </p>

    <h2>Graph-Directed IFS (GIFS)</h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>Graph-Directed IFS</strong> (GDIFS, introduced by Mauldin &amp; Williams 1988,
      also called GIFS in the IFStile literature) generalises the single-attractor case to
      a system of multiple interleaved attractor sets whose equations refer to each other.
      Instead of a single equation
      <em>A = ⋃ f<sub>i</sub>(A)</em>, a GDIFS with attractors
      <em>A</em><sub>1</sub>, …, <em>A<sub>k</sub></em> satisfies a system:
    </p>
    <p set:html={"$$A_j = \\bigcup_{i} f_{ij}(A_{\\sigma(i,j)})$$"}></p>
    <p>
      where each map <em>f<sub>ij</sub></em> sends one attractor into another according to a
      directed graph (the <em>dependency graph</em>). Under suitable expansiveness conditions
      the system has a unique tuple of non-empty compact sets
      (A<sub>1</sub>, …, A<sub>k</sub>) satisfying all equations simultaneously.
    </p>
    <p>
      GDIFS naturally arise in <strong>substitution tilings</strong>: a tiling with multiple
      prototile types (e.g. the <a href="/ifs/cap">CAP / hat monotile</a> with four metatile
      types H, T, P, F, or the <a href="/ifs/robinson-triangles">Robinson triangle</a> with two
      types) can be described as a GDIFS where each attractor is the shape of one prototile and
      the maps encode the substitution rule.
    </p>

    <h2>Further Reading</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="https://tilings.math.uni-bielefeld.de/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tilings Encyclopedia</a> —
        comprehensive reference for substitution tilings: inflation factors, Hausdorff dimensions, and bibliographic sources.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://larryriddle.agnesscott.org/ifs/ifs.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Larry Riddle's Classic IFS</a> —
        geometrically described IFS attractors with matrix forms, L-systems, and similarity dimensions.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/tiling" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tiling Facebook Group</a> —
        active community discussing tilings, self-similar sets, and IFS fractals; original discovery posts and informal results often appear here first.
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/tools/aifs">AIFS Language Reference</a> —
        algebraic representation used to define all fractals in this encyclopedia.
      </li>
      <li>
        Mekhontsev, D. (2019).
        <a href="https://epub.ub.uni-greifswald.de/frontdoor/index/index/docId/2479" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          <em>An algebraic framework for finding and analyzing self-affine tiles and fractals</em>
        </a>.
        Doctoral thesis, Ernst-Moritz-Arndt-Universität Greifswald.
        Establishes the algebraic foundations of the IFStile algorithms.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>About This Site</h2>
    <p>
      This encyclopedia is an open reference for IFS attractors.
    </p>
    <h3>Live rendering</h3>
    <p>
      Every fractal image you see — in the catalog, on each entry page, and on the landing page —
      is <strong>rendered live in your browser</strong>. There are no pre-generated images stored
      on the server. Each attractor is computed on demand by
      <a href="https://github.com/mekhontsev/ifstile" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>ifslib</strong></a>,
      a WebAssembly module compiled from the IFStile source. The AIFS program embedded in each
      entry is passed directly to <code>ifslib</code> running
      inside a Web Worker, and the resulting pixel buffer is drawn onto the canvas — all
      client-side, with no server involvement.
    </p>
    <p>
      Progressive rendering is used: the canvas first shows a quick low-resolution preview
      (32 px, 64 px, …) that sharpens up to the full resolution in the background.
      Clicking any canvas opens the attractor in the full
      <a href="https://app.ifstile.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IFStile web app</a>
      for interactive exploration.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mathematical formulas are rendered with
      <a href="https://katex.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KaTeX</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Content is licensed under
      <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        CC BY 4.0
      </a>.
      Contributions welcome on
      <a href="https://github.com/ifsdb/ifsdb.github.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        GitHub
      </a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
